## 1. Purpose
This standard defines the secure configuration baselines that all in-scope systems **shall** meet, and requires continuous detection and remediation of drift from those baselines. Consistent hardening reduces attack surface across the [AWS] estate, operating systems, containers, and [Snowflake] that store and process PHI.

## 2. Scope
Applies to all [AWS] accounts and managed services, OS instances (EC2/[other]), container images and orchestration, and [Snowflake] account/object configuration in scope of the ISMS. New systems **shall** be provisioned from a hardened baseline; existing systems **shall** be brought into conformance.

## 3. Standard (requirements)
1. All in-scope systems **shall** be configured to a documented hardening baseline derived from a recognized benchmark (see §4); deviations **shall** be justified and recorded.
2. Baselines **shall** be implemented as code (IaC, golden images, baked configuration) so configuration is repeatable, reviewable, and version-controlled per `change-management-policy.md.template`.
3. Configuration drift from baseline **shall** be detected continuously (see §8) and remediated or risk-accepted within the SLAs in `vulnerability-and-patch-management.md.template`.
4. Default credentials, unused services, and unnecessary ports/protocols **shall** be removed or disabled before a system handles production traffic.
5. Logging, encryption, and access controls **shall** be enabled by default per `logging-and-monitoring-policy.md.template`, `cryptography-and-key-management.md.template`, and `../access/access-control-policy.md.template`.
6. Only approved, hardened base images from trusted registries **shall** be used; images **shall** be scanned per `vulnerability-and-patch-management.md.template`.
7. Baselines **shall** be reviewed at least annually and on benchmark updates.

## 4. Benchmark References
Baselines **shall** be derived from and traceable to:
- **CIS Benchmarks** for the relevant platforms ([CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark], [CIS Amazon Linux / Ubuntu], [CIS Docker / Kubernetes]).
- **AWS Foundational Security Best Practices** (via AWS Security Hub standards).
- Vendor hardening guidance for [Snowflake] and other platform services.
[Record the exact benchmark version and any tuned/excepted controls in the baseline-as-code repository.]

## 5. AWS Account Baseline
- Multi-account structure via [AWS Organizations] with [OUs] separating prod/non-prod and security/log-archive accounts.
- Organization-wide guardrails via [Service Control Policies]; root account secured (MFA, no access keys, no routine use).
- [Security Hub] (with CIS/AWS FSBP standards), [GuardDuty], [AWS Config], and [CloudTrail] enabled in all accounts/regions and aggregated to a [security/log-archive] account.
- IAM follows least privilege; human access federated via [IdP/SSO]; workloads use IAM roles; no long-lived access keys (`cryptography-and-key-management.md.template`).
- S3 public access blocked at account level; default encryption enforced; EBS encryption-by-default on.

## 6. OS & Container Baseline
- Minimal/golden images; only required packages; CIS-aligned OS settings; host firewall default-deny.
- EDR/agent and patch agent installed where applicable (`endpoint-security-policy.md.template`).
- Containers run as non-root, read-only root filesystem where feasible, no privileged mode, dropped capabilities, resource limits set; secrets injected at runtime, never baked into images.
- Image provenance verified; base images patched per the vulnerability SLAs.

## 7. Snowflake Baseline
- SSO/[OIDC/SAML] and MFA enforced; key-pair or OAuth for service accounts; no shared credentials.
- Network policies restrict access to approved IP ranges/[PrivateLink]; [Tri-Secret Secure / CMK] where required (`cryptography-and-key-management.md.template`).
- Role hierarchy follows least privilege; `ACCOUNTADMIN`/`SECURITYADMIN` use is restricted and monitored; PHI-bearing objects governed by row/column access policies and masking.
- `ACCESS_HISTORY`/account usage logging enabled and exported per `logging-and-monitoring-policy.md.template`.

## 8. Drift Detection & Enforcement
1. **[AWS Config]** rules (and conformance packs aligned to CIS/FSBP) **shall** continuously evaluate resource configuration against the baseline; non-conformant resources generate findings.
2. IaC scanning in CI (`secure-sdlc-policy.md.template`) **shall** prevent non-conformant configuration from being merged.
3. Detected drift **shall** be triaged, and remediated (preferably auto-remediation for safe cases) or risk-accepted within SLA.
4. [Security Hub] aggregates configuration findings for tracking and reporting.

## 9. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Platform Engineering Lead] | Owns baselines-as-code; implements and updates hardening; remediates drift. |
| [Security Officer] | Approves baselines and benchmark selection; oversees drift findings. |
| Service Owners | Keep their systems conformant; justify deviations. |
| [CTO] | Approves this standard and material baseline exceptions. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 10. Exceptions
Deviations from a baseline require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Security Officer], time-bound, recorded in the exceptions log, and (where automated) suppressed in [AWS Config]/[Security Hub] with a linked justification.

## 11. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
Compliance is measured by [AWS Config]/[Security Hub] conformance scores, IaC scan results, and benchmark assessments, reviewed during internal audit and management review. Non-conformance is tracked to closure. Violations are handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template`.

